<Layout title="Module 6 – Wound Care">
  <h1>Module 6: Wound Care</h1>
  <p>
    Effective wound care requires accurate assessment, maintenance of a moist wound
    environment, prevention of infection, and selection of appropriate dressings. The nurse
    plays a central role in monitoring healing and communicating changes to the care team.
  </p>

  <h2>Wound Classification</h2>
  <h3>By Cause</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Intentional:</strong> Surgical incisions, biopsies — made under controlled conditions.</li>
    <li><strong>Unintentional:</strong> Traumatic injuries — lacerations, abrasions, punctures.</li>
    <li><strong>Pressure injuries:</strong> From sustained pressure, shear, or friction.</li>
    <li><strong>Vascular ulcers:</strong> Arterial (ischemic) or venous (stasis) in origin.</li>
    <li><strong>Diabetic foot ulcers:</strong> Neuropathic or ischemic in nature.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>By Depth</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Superficial:</strong> Involves epidermis only.</li>
    <li><strong>Partial-thickness:</strong> Extends through epidermis and into dermis.</li>
    <li><strong>Full-thickness:</strong> Through dermis into subcutaneous tissue; may involve fascia, muscle, or bone.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Wound Healing</h2>
  <h3>Phases</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Timeframe</th><th>Key Events</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Hemostasis</td>
        <td>Immediate – minutes</td>
        <td>Vasoconstriction, platelet aggregation, clot formation</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Inflammatory</td>
        <td>1–4 days</td>
        <td>Vasodilation, increased permeability, phagocytosis; wound appears red, warm, swollen</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Proliferative</td>
        <td>4–21 days</td>
        <td>Granulation tissue formation, re-epithelialization, wound contraction</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Maturation (Remodeling)</td>
        <td>21 days – 2 years</td>
        <td>Collagen remodeling; scar formation; wound gains tensile strength</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <h3>Types of Healing</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary intention:</strong> Wound edges are approximated (sutured, stapled, steri-stripped); minimal scarring.</li>
    <li><strong>Secondary intention:</strong> Wound left open; heals from the bottom up; more scarring and longer healing time.</li>
    <li><strong>Tertiary (delayed primary) intention:</strong> Wound initially left open, then closed after infection is controlled.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Wound Assessment (MEASURES Mnemonic)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>M</strong>easure: Length × width × depth (cm)</li>
    <li><strong>E</strong>xude: Amount (none, scant, moderate, large) and character (serous, serosanguineous, sanguineous, purulent)</li>
    <li><strong>A</strong>ppearance: Wound bed tissue type (granulation, slough, eschar, epithelial)</li>
    <li><strong>S</strong>uffering: Pain assessment before, during, after care</li>
    <li><strong>U</strong>ndermining/Tunneling: Extend tissue damage beneath wound edges</li>
    <li><strong>R</strong>e-evaluate: Reassess regularly and document changes</li>
    <li><strong>E</strong>dge: Wound margins — attached, rolled, macerated, hyperkeratotic</li>
    <li><strong>S</strong>urrounding skin: Periwound condition — erythema, induration, maceration, satellite lesions</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sterile Technique &amp; Dressing Changes</h2>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Key Rule</strong>
    Use sterile technique (surgical asepsis) for all wound care involving open or surgical
    wounds. Clean technique may be acceptable for some chronic wounds per facility policy.
  </div>
  <h3>Procedure</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Verify order; gather supplies; perform hand hygiene.</li>
    <li>Provide privacy; explain procedure; assess pain level and medicate if ordered.</li>
    <li>Set up sterile field using sterile drape; open supplies using sterile technique.</li>
    <li>Don clean gloves; remove old dressing (note appearance and amount of drainage).</li>
    <li>Discard soiled dressing; remove clean gloves; perform hand hygiene.</li>
    <li>Don sterile gloves.</li>
    <li>Cleanse wound with ordered solution (normal saline is most common); cleanse from wound center outward or clean to dirty.</li>
    <li>Apply appropriate dressing; secure with tape, wrap, or fixation device.</li>
    <li>Remove gloves; perform hand hygiene; document.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Wound Drainage</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Significance</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Serous</td><td>Clear, watery</td><td>Normal in early healing</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Serosanguineous</td><td>Pink-tinged, watery</td><td>Normal during inflammatory / proliferative phases</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sanguineous</td><td>Bright red, bloody</td><td>Active bleeding; may indicate vessel damage</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Purulent</td><td>Thick, yellow/green/brown; foul odor</td><td>Infection — report immediately</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Wound Drains</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Jackson-Pratt (JP):</strong> Closed, self-contained suction drain (bulb); compress bulb after emptying to re-establish suction.</li>
    <li><strong>Hemovac:</strong> Larger closed suction drain; compress disc after emptying.</li>
    <li><strong>Penrose:</strong> Open, passive gravity drain — place on sterile gauze; change dressing when saturated.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Signs of Wound Infection</h2>
  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Report These Immediately</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Increased redness, warmth, or edema beyond the wound margins</li>
      <li>Purulent drainage or foul odor</li>
      <li>Fever and elevated WBC (systemic infection signs)</li>
      <li>Wound dehiscence (separation of wound edges) or evisceration (protrusion of organs)</li>
      <li>Increased pain beyond what is expected</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Granulation tissue:</strong> Pink/red, moist, beefy tissue that indicates healthy wound healing.</li>
    <li><strong>Slough:</strong> Yellow, stringy, moist necrotic tissue that must be removed for healing to progress.</li>
    <li><strong>Eschar:</strong> Black, hard, leathery necrotic tissue; may be stable (leave intact) or unstable (requires debridement).</li>
    <li><strong>Dehiscence:</strong> Partial or complete separation of wound edges.</li>
    <li><strong>Evisceration:</strong> Protrusion of internal organs through a wound opening — medical emergency.</li>
    <li><strong>Debridement:</strong> Removal of necrotic tissue to promote healing.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
